<section xml:id="sec_Groups_Examples">
  <title>Examples</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      There are multitudes upon multitudes of groups besides those we've seen so far.
      Some are modifications of groups we are very familiar with.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="example_Groups_Rstar_group">
      <statement>
      <p>
        The set <m>{\mathbb R} \setminus \{0 \}</m> of non-zero real numbers is written as <m>{\mathbb R}^{\ast}</m>.
        Let's prove that <m>({\mathbb R}^{\ast}, \cdot)</m> is a group.
        <ol type="1">
          <li>
            <p>
              Closure: Suppose <m>a, b \in {\mathbb R}^{\ast}</m>.
              Then to prove closure we must show <m>ab \in {\mathbb R}^{\ast}</m>;
              that is, we must show (i) <m>ab \in {\mathbb R}</m> and (ii)
              <m>ab \neq 0</m>: (i): Since <m>a, b \in {\mathbb R}</m>,
              and we know <m>{\mathbb R}</m> is closed under multiplication,
              then <m>ab \in {\mathbb R}</m>. (ii): Suppose <m>ab = 0</m>.
              Then as we noted in <xref ref="subsec_Preliminaries_OpsAndRels">Section</xref>,
              we know either <m>a = 0</m> or <m>b = 0</m>.
              But <m>a, b \in {\mathbb R}^{\ast}</m>; i.e.
              <m>a, b \neq 0</m>.
              So we have a contradiction.
              Hence <m>ab \neq 0</m>.
              Therefore <m>ab \in {\mathbb R}^{\ast}</m>;
              and so <m>{\mathbb R}^{\ast}</m> is closed under multiplication.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        To finish the proof that <m>{\mathbb R}^{\ast}</m> is a group,
        we must establish axioms (2) through (4) in <xref ref="definition_Groups_group_definition">Definition</xref>.
        We leave this up to you in the following exercise:
      </p>
      <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_Rstar_group">
        <statement>
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Finish proving that <m>({\mathbb R}^{\ast}, \cdot)</m> is a group.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Either prove or disprove that <m>({\mathbb R}^{\ast}, +)</m> is a group.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the order of <m>({\mathbb R}^{\ast}, \cdot)</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_C_star">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>{\mathbb C}^{\ast}</m> be the set of non-zero complex numbers.
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Why is <m>{\mathbb C}^{\ast}</m> not a group under the operation of complex addition?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove <m>{\mathbb C}^{\ast}</m> is a group under the operation of (complex) multiplication.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is <m>| ({\mathbb C}^{\ast}, \cdot) |</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>({\mathbb C}^{\ast}, \cdot)</m> an abelian group?
                Justify your answer.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <remark>
      <p>
        Groups based on sets of numbers that <em>include</em> 0
        (such as <m>{\mathbb R}, {\mathbb C}, {\mathbb Q}</m>)
        are assumed to have the group operation <m>+</m>
        (unless otherwise stated).
        For groups based on sets of numbers that <em>exclude</em>
        <m>0</m> such as <m>{\mathbb R^\ast}, {\mathbb C^\ast}, {\mathbb Q^\ast}</m>,
        the group operation is assumed to be multiplication
        (unless otherwise stated).
      </p>
    </remark>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_15">
      <statement>
        <ol type="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              Why is it impossible for a set of complex numbers <m>S</m> which has more than one element and includes 0 to be a group under multiplication?
              Why is the condition <m>|S|>1</m> necessary?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Why is it impossible for a set of complex numbers <m>S</m> that excludes 0 to be a group under addition?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Some groups use exotic operations that you may never have seen before:
    </p>
    <example xml:id="example_Groups_S_group">
      <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>S = {\mathbb R} \setminus \{ -1 \}</m> and define a binary operation on <m>S</m> by <m>a \ast b = a + b +ab</m>.
        It turns out that <m>(S, \ast)</m> is an abelian group.
        We will prove closure and the commutative property;
        the rest of the proof will be left to you.
      </p>
      <ol type="1">
        <li>
          <p>
            Closure: Suppose <m>a, b \in S</m>.
            We need to show that <m>a \ast b \in S</m>;
            i.e. that (i) <m>a \ast b \in {\mathbb R}</m> and (ii) <m>a \ast b \neq -1</m>.
          </p>
          <ol type="i">
            <li>
              <p>
                By the closure of <m>({\mathbb R}, +), (a + b) \in {\mathbb R}</m>.
                By the closure of <m>({\mathbb R}, \ast), (ab) \in {\mathbb R}</m>.
                Finally, by the closure of <m>({\mathbb R}, +), ((a + b) + (ab)) \in {\mathbb R}</m>.
                It follows that <m>a \ast b \in {\mathbb R}</m>,
                so <m>S</m> is closed under <m>\ast</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose that <m>a \ast b = -1</m>.
                Then by definition of <m>\ast</m>, <m>a + b +ab = -1</m>.
                Solving for <m>a</m>, we get <m>a = \dfrac{-1(b + 1)}{b + 1}</m>,
                or <m>a = -1</m> But since <m>a \in S, a \neq -1</m>.
                So we have a contradiction.
                Hence <m>a \ast b \neq -1</m>.
                This completes the proof that <m>(S, \ast)</m> is closed.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Commutativity: Suppose <m>a, b \in S</m>.
            We need to show that <m>a \ast b = b \ast a</m>:
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  First, by the definition of the operation <m>\ast</m> we have <m>a \ast b = a + b +ab</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Next, since <m>{\mathbb R}</m> is commutative under addition and multiplication,
                  it follows that <m>a + b = b + a</m> and <m>ab = ba</m>.
                  Adding these two equations, we have <m>(a + b) + (ab) = (b + a) + (ba)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  By the definition of <m>\ast</m>,
                  <m>(b + a) + (ba) = b \ast a</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Putting all these equalities together,
                  we have <m>a \ast b = a + b +ab = b + a + ba = b \ast a</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          This completes the proof that <m>(S, \ast)</m> is commutative.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_S_group">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Finish the proof that <m>(S, \ast)</m> is an abelian group.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      The following example shows a famous
      (among mathematicians!)
      group that has important applications in physics:
    </p>
    <example xml:id="example_Groups_quaternions">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <em>quaternion group</em><idx><h>Quaternion group (<m>Q_8</m>)</h></idx>
          (denoted by <m>Q_8</m>)
          consists of 8 elements, which are commonly denoted as follows:
          <m>1</m>, <m>i</m>, <m>j</m>,
          <m>k</m>, <m>-1</m>, <m>-i</m>, <m>-j</m>, <m>-k</m>.
          The Cayley table of <m>Q_8</m> is determined by the following relations:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                1 is the identity;
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                -1 commutes with all other elements, and <m>(-1)^2=1</m>;
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>-1 \cdot i = -i, -1 \cdot j = -j, -1 \cdot k = -k</m>;
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>i^2 = j^2=k^2 = -1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>i \cdot j = k, j \cdot k = i, k \cdot i=j</m>;
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>j \cdot i = -k, k \cdot j=-i, i \cdot k = -j</m> .
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_QuatEx">
      <statement>
        <ol type="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the information given above to complete the Cayley table for <m>Q_8</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the inverses of all of the elements of <m>Q_8</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Other groups use operations that are in built up from other groups.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_integer_coordinate_plane">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>H = {\mathbb Z} \times {\mathbb Z}</m>
          (all integer coordinate-pairs).
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Define a binary operation <m>\circ</m> on <m>H</m> by <m>(a,b) \circ (c,d) = (a + c , b + d)</m>,
                for <m>(a,b), (c,d) \in H</m>.
                This operation is in fact just coordinate-pair addition.
                Is <m>(H , \circ)</m> a group?
                If so, is <m>(H , \circ)</m> abelian?
                Justify your answers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Define a binary operation <m>\circ</m> on <m>H</m> by <m>(a,b) \circ (c,d) = (ac , bd)</m>,
                for <m>(a,b), (c,d) \in H</m>.
                This is just coordinate-pair multiplication.
                Is <m>(H , \circ)</m> a group?
                If so, is <m>(H , \circ)</m> abelian?
                Justify your answers.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_19">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>G = {\mathbb R}^{\ast} \times {\mathbb Z}</m> (all pairs such that the first element is a nonzero real number,
          and the second is an integer)
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Define a binary operation <m>\circ</m> on <m>G</m> by <m>(a,m) \circ (b,n) = (a+b, m+n)</m>.
                Is <m>(G , \circ)</m> a group?
                If so, is <m>(G , \circ)</m> abelian?
                Justify your answers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Define a binary operation <m>\circ</m> on <m>G</m> by <m>(a,m) \circ (b,n) = (ab, mn)</m>.
                Is <m>(G , \circ)</m> a group?
                If so, is <m>(G , \circ)</m> abelian?
                Justify your answers.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Define a binary operation <m>\circ</m> on <m>G</m> by <m>(a,m) \circ (b,n) = (ab,
                m+n)</m>.
                Is <m>(G , \circ)</m> a group?
                If so, is <m>(G , \circ)</m> abelian?
                Justify your answers.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      The previous two exercises follow a pattern that we may generalize:
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {defProductOfGroups} Given two groups <m>G</m> and <m>H</m>,
          we define the <em>product</em>
              <idx><h>Product</h><h>of groups</h></idx>
          of groups <m>G</m> and <m>H</m>
          (denoted by <m>G \times H</m>)
          as the set of pairs <m>\left\{(g,h),
          g \in G, h \in H \right\}</m>.
          If <m>(g_1, h_1)</m> and <m>(g_2,h_2)</m> are two elements of <m>G \times H</m>,
          then we define the group operation <m>(g_1, h_1) \circ (g_2, h_2)</m> as follows:
          <me>
            (g_1, h_1) \circ (g_2, h_2) := (g_1g_2, h_1h_2)
          </me>,
          where <m>g_1g_2</m> uses the group operation in <m>G</m> and <m>h_1h_2</m> uses the group operation in <m>H</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_prod_of_groups">
      <statement>
        <ol type="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider <m>(3,6)</m> and <m>(2,4)</m> as elements of <m>{\mathbb Z}_7 \times {\mathbb Z}_7</m>.
              Compute <m>(3,6) \circ (2,4)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider <m>(3,6)</m> and <m>(2,4)</m> as elements of <m>{\mathbb R}^{\ast} \times {\mathbb Z}_{10}</m>.
              Compute <m>(3,6) \circ (2,4)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider <m>(3,6)</m> and <m>(2,4)</m> as elements of <m>{\mathbb Q}^{\ast} \times {\mathbb Q}^{\ast}</m>.
              Compute <m>(3,6) \circ (2,4)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_prod_group">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the product of two groups is a group.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_Z_2_n">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>{\mathbb Z}_2^n = \{ (a_1, a_2, \ldots,
          a_n) : a_i \in {\mathbb Z}_2 \}</m>.
          Define a binary operation on <m>{\mathbb Z}_2^n</m>
          (which we will denote as <sq>+</sq>)
          by
          <me>
            (a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_n) + (b_1, b_2, \ldots, b_n) = (a_1 \oplus  b_1, a_2 \oplus b_2, \ldots, a_n+b_n)
          </me>,
          where <m>\oplus</m> denotes addition in <m>{\mathbb Z}_2</m>.
          Prove that <m>{\mathbb Z}_2^n</m> is a group under this operation.
          This group is important in algebraic coding theory.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      In previous chapters we've used Cayley tables
          <idx><h>Cayley table</h></idx>
      to describe group operations.
      With Cayley tables we can prove a set and operation are a group even when we don't know what the elements in the set really are or what the binary operation is.
    </p>
    <p>
      The next two exercises are very useful in the subsequent exercises.
    </p>
