      The same is true for any <m>{\mathbb Z}_n</m>.
      It follows that in order to get a group under modular multiplication using the elements of <m>{\mathbb Z}_n</m>,
      we'll have to kick out the non-relatively prime numbers in order to guarantee that every element has an inverse.
