    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_27">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the Cayley table in <xref ref="CayleyU8">Table</xref> represents a group.
          (Note that associativity holds because we already know that modular multiplication is associative.)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_28">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Is the group in <xref ref="CayleyU8">Table</xref> abelian?
          Justify your answer.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      For convenience, let's define some notation:
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {DefnOfUnits} The set of nonzero numbers in
          <m>{\mathbb Z}_n</m> that are relatively prime to <m>n</m> is called the
          <term>set of units of <m>{\mathbb Z}_n</m></term>,
          denoted by <term><m>U(n)</m></term><idx><h>Units</h><h>group of (<m>U(n)</m>)</h></idx>.
              <idx><h>Group</h><h>of units <m>U(n)</m></h></idx>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We have just seen that <m>U(8)</m> is a group under modular multiplication.
      One might suspect that <m>U(n)</m> is a group for any <m>n</m>.
      For starters,
      it is clear that <m>1</m> serves as an identity element,
      because <m>1\cdot k \equiv k \cdot 1 \equiv k</m> mod <m>n</m> for any <m>n</m>.
      In fact, <m>U(n)</m> is an abelian group,
      as you will show in the following exercises.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_U_n__abgroup">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In this exercise,
          we prove that <m>U(n)</m> is a group under multiplication mod <m>n</m> for any <m>n</m>.
          We know that modular multiplication is associative,
          so it remains to show the closure and inverse properties.
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Fill in the blanks to show that <m>U(n)</m> is closed under modular multiplication: Let <m>k,m</m> be arbitrary elements of <m>U(n)</m>.
                It follows that both <m>k</m> and
                <em><m>~\lt 1>~</m></em>
                are relatively prime to <em><m>~\lt 2>~</m></em>.
                So neither <m>k</m> nor <em><m>~\lt 3>~</m></em>
                has any prime factors in common with
                <em><m>~\lt 4>~</m></em>.
                It follows that the product <em><m>~\lt 5>~</m></em>
                also has no prime factors in common with
                <em><m>~\lt 6>~</m></em>.
                Furthermore, the remainder of <em><m>~\lt 7>~</m></em>
                under division by <em><m>~\lt 8>~</m></em>
                also has no prime factors in common with
                <em><m>~\lt 9>~</m></em>.
                Therefore the product of <em><m>~\lt 10>~</m></em>
                and <em><m>~\lt 11>~</m></em>
                under modular multiplication is also an element of
                <em><m>~\lt 12>~</m></em>,
                so <em><m>~\lt 13>~</m></em> is closed under modular multiplication.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                It remains to show that <m>U(n)</m> is closed under inverse.
                Suppose that <m>m \in U(n)</m> and <m>x</m> is the inverse of <m>m</m>.
                What modular equation must <m>x</m> satisfy? (*Hint*)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that the equation in <m>x</m> that you wrote in part (b) has a solution as long as <m>m</m> is relatively prime to <m>n</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_UnAbel">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that <m>U(n)</m> is abelian.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <remark xml:id="UnMul">
      <p>
        Whenever we talk about the group <m>U(n)</m>,
        we always assume the operation is multiplication.
        Similarly, whenever we talk about <m>{\mathbb Z}_n</m>,
        we always assume the operation is addition.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Groups of matrices</title>
    <p>
      Matrices provide many examples of interesting groups.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_M2x2_group">
      <statement>
        <p>
              <idx><h>Matrix groups</h><h><m>M_2</m></h></idx>
          We use <m>{\mathbb M}_2 ( {\mathbb C})</m> to denote the set of all <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices with complex entries.
          That is
          <me>
            {\mathbb M}_2 ( {\mathbb C}) = \left\{ \begin{pmatrix}a \amp  b \\ c \amp  d \end{pmatrix}  ~|~ a,b,c,d \in {\mathbb C} \right\}
          </me>
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that <m>{\mathbb M}_2 ( {\mathbb C})</m> a group under matrix addition.
                Is it abelian?
                If so, prove it: if not, find a counterexample.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the order of this group?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>{\mathbb M}_2 ( {\mathbb C})</m> a group under matrix multiplication?
                Is it abelian?
                Justify your answers.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_Mn_group">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>{\mathbb M}_n ( {\mathbb C})</m> be the set of all
          <m>n\times n</m> matrices with complex entries.
          Show that <m>{\mathbb M}_n ( {\mathbb C})</m> is a group under matrix addition.
          What is the order of this group?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      There are multiplicative groups of <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices as well,
      but not all matrices can be included.
      To specify those which are included,
      we need the following definition
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {MatDet} For the <m>2\times 2</m> matrix <m>A = \begin{pmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{pmatrix}</m>,
          the quantity <m>ad-bc</m> is called the
          <em>determinant</em><idx><h>Determinant</h><h>of a 2 <times/> 2 matrix</h></idx> of <m>A</m> and is denoted by <m>\det(A)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      The following exercise is algebraically a little complicated,
      but turns out to be essential in order to prove properties of multiplicative groups of matrices.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_detMult">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Using matrix multiplication and the definition of determinant,
          prove that if <m>A = \begin{pmatrix}a \amp  b \\ c \amp  d \end{pmatrix}</m> and <m>B = \begin{pmatrix}e \amp  f \\ g \amp  h \end{pmatrix}</m>, then
          <me>
            \det(AB) =  \det(A)\det(B)
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>.
          This is known as the <term>determinant product formula</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      We're now ready to define a set of
      <m>2\times 2</m> matrices which is suitable to form a multiplicative group.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {GL2} Let <m>GL_2({\mathbb C})</m> be the subset of
          <m>{\mathbb M}_2 ( {\mathbb C})</m> consisting of matrices <m>A</m> such that
          <me>
            A = \begin{pmatrix}a \amp  b \\ c \amp  d \end{pmatrix}  \text{ and }  \det(A) \neq 0
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      The proof that <m>GL_2({\mathbb C})</m> is a group is contained in the following exercise.
    </p>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise_Groups_GL2_group">
      <statement>
        <p>
              <idx><h>Matrix groups</h><h><m>GL_2</m></h></idx>
              <idx><h>Matrices</h><h>invertible</h></idx>
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that for any matrix <m>A \in GL_2(\mathbb{C})</m>,
                the matrix
                <me>
                  B = \frac{1}{\det(A)}\begin{pmatrix}d \amp  -b \\ -c \amp  a \end{pmatrix}
                </me>
                satisfies
                <me>
                  AB = BA = I
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Using <xref ref="exercise_Groups_detMult">Exercise</xref>,
                show that <m>GL_2(\mathbb{C})</m> is closed under matrix multiplication.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that matrix multiplication in <m>GL_2(\mathbb{C})</m> is associative.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Complete the proof that <m>GL_2(\mathbb{C})</m> is a group under matrix multiplication.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>GL_2(\mathbb C)</m> is called the 2-dimensional
          <term>general linear group</term>
          over the complex numbers.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove or disprove: <m>GL_2(\mathbb C)</m> is abelian.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      It turns out that we can define a multiplicative group of
      <m>n \times n</m> matrices for any positive integer <m>n</m>,
      in similar fashion as we defined <m>GL_2(\mathbb{C})</m>.
      Rather than using determinant,
      we present an alternative way of characterizing the
      <m>n \times n</m> matrices that are suitable members of a multiplicative group.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {inversibleMatrix} An <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>A</m> is called <em>invertible</em>
              <idx><h>Matrix</h><h>nvertible</h></idx>
          if there exists a <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>B</m> such that <m>AB = BA = I_n</m>,
          where <m>I_n</m> is the <m>n \times n</m> identity matrix.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      It is fairly straightforward to prove the group properties under matrix multiplication for this limited set of matrices:
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the set of <m>n \times n</m> invertible matrices with complex entries form a group under matrix multiplication.
          You may assume that matrix multiplication is associative
          (this is proved in another chapter).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          {Gln} The set of <m>n \times n</m> invertible matrices is called the <m>n</m> dimensional
          <term>general linear group</term>,
          and is denoted by <m>GL_n(\mathbb{C})</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
</section>